sec.p:
Differences among individuals in cortisol responses to stress result from a complex interplay between genetic and environmental factors. The genetic contribution to the variability in HPA axis reactivity is believed to arise from DNA variations (i.e., polymorphisms) in the genes encoding neurotransmitters involved in HPA axis regulation. Overall, heritable influences account for approximately 62 percent of the etiological variance in basal glucocorticoid levels (Bartels et al. 2003). Recent candidate gene association studies using laboratory-based stress procedures also have implicated multiple gene variants in explaining some of the variance in cortisol responses to stress, including polymorphisms in the following genes:
Nr3c1, which encodes a glucocorticoid receptor protein (Wust et al. 2004);
Nr3c2, which encodes a mineralocorticoid receptor protein (DeRijk et al. 2006);
FKBP5 (Ising et al. 2008);
CRFR1, which encodes the CRF receptor 1 protein (Clarke and Schumann 2009);
CRF-BP, which encodes CRF binding protein (Wang et al. 2007);
GABRA6, which encodes the GABA receptor subunit alpha-6 protein (Uhart et al. 2004);
OPRM1, which encodes the mu opioid receptor protein (Chong et al. 2006); and
SLC6A4, which encodes a serotonin transporter protein (Way and Taylor 2010).
